===Income===
New York City has a high degree of [[income disparity]] as indicated by its [[Gini Coefficient]] of 0.5 for the city overall and 0.6 for Manhattan.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=Inequality |url=http://www.hks.harvard.edu/var/ezp_site/storage/fckeditor/file/pdfs/centers-programs/centers/taubman/working_papers/glaeser_08_inequality.pdf |at=page 2, introduction |publisher=harvard.edu |accessdate=March 30, 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt; The disparity is driven by [[real wage|wage growth]] in [[Rate schedule (federal income tax)|high-income brackets]], while wages have stagnated for middle and lower-income brackets. In the first quarter of 2014, the average weekly wage in New York County (Manhattan) was $2,749, representing the highest total among large counties in the United States.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.bls.gov/news.release/cewqtr.nr0.htm |title=County Employment and Wages Summary |publisher=Bureau of Labor Statistics, U.S. Department of Labor |date=September 18, 2014 |accessdate=September 21, 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 2013, New York City had the highest number of  [[billionaire]]s of any city in the world, higher than the next five U.S. cities combined,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/top-20-cities-where-billionaires-live-2013-5 |title=The 20 Cities Where The Most Billionaires Live |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=May 7, 2013}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-05-10/mumbai/39167878_1_billionaires-millionaires-top-10-cities |title=Mumbai sixth among top 10 global cities on billionaire count |work=[[Times of India]] |publisher=2013-05-10}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2013/may/08/cities-top-millionaires-billionaires |title=Which cities do the world's millionaires and billionaires live in? |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=May 8, 2013}}&lt;/ref&gt; including former [[Mayor of New York City|Mayor]] [[Michael R. Bloomberg]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.forbes.com/profile/michael-bloomberg/ |title=The World's Billionaires – Michael Bloomberg |work=Forbes |accessdate=February 24, 2013}}
&lt;/ref&gt; New York also had the highest density of [[millionaire]]s per capita among major U.S. cities in 2014, at 4.6% of residents.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/08/04/luxury/most-millionaires-cities/index.html?iid=HP_LN |title=Want to meet a millionaire? Here's where to go |author=Gregory Wallace |publisher=CNN |date=August 4, 2014 |accessdate=August 4, 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt; Lower Manhattan has been experiencing a [[baby boom]], with the area south of [[Canal Street (Manhattan)|Canal Street]] witnessing 1,086 births in 2010, 12% greater than 2009 and over twice the number born in 2001.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20120111/downtown/downtown-baby-boom-sees-12-percent-increase-births |title=Downtown Baby Boom Sees 12 Percent Increase in Births |author=Julie Shapiro |publisher=DNAinfo New York |date=January 11, 2012 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}&lt;/ref&gt;
